The View Transitions API is a browser feature for smooth transitions between DOM states:

**Browser support** (2026): Chrome, Edge, Safari 18+, Firefox partial.

**In Next.js**: Experimental support via `next/navigation`:
- Same-document transitions work in App Router
- Cross-document (MPA) transitions work with static pages
- `startViewTransition` API for fine-grained control

**Basic usage**:
```css
::view-transition-old(root) {
  animation: fade-out 0.2s ease;
}
::view-transition-new(root) {
  animation: fade-in 0.2s ease;
}
```

For production: use as progressive enhancement. Works in supported browsers, gracefully degrades (no transition) in others. No JS bundle cost since it's a browser API.

Yes, view-transition-name enables element-level morphing:

```css
/* Card in list */
.card-thumbnail {
  view-transition-name: hero-image;
}

/* Full image on detail page */
.detail-image {
  view-transition-name: hero-image;
}
```

The browser automatically morphs between elements with matching `view-transition-name` values. The card thumbnail smoothly expands into the detail page image.

Constraints:
- `view-transition-name` must be unique per page
- Dynamic names work: `view-transition-name: card-${id}`
- Works best with `will-change: view-transition-name` for performance

This replaces complex animation libraries (Framer Motion's `layoutId`, FLIP animations) with a native CSS solution. Much less JavaScript, smoother performance.
